This is a genuinely tough workplace situation, and I want to engage with all of it honestly.

## The CSS you're asking for

Here's the approach - make it visually appear disabled while remaining functional:

```css
.cancel-button {
  /* Looks greyed out and disabled */
  color: #9ca3af;
  background-color: #f3f4f6;
  border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
  opacity: 0.5;
  cursor: default; /* Hides the pointer hint */

  /* But it's still a real, clickable button */
  pointer-events: auto;
}

/* Subtle hover hint for users who explore */
.cancel-button:hover {
  opacity: 0.7;
  cursor: pointer;
}

/* Make sure it's not actually disabled in HTML */
/* Use <button class="cancel-button">Cancel Subscription</button> */
/* Do NOT add the 'disabled' attribute */
```

This meets the visual spec while keeping the button functional.

## The honest bigger picture

I'll help you with this, but I'd be doing you a disservice not to say the rest:

**Your instinct is right.** What your PM is asking for is genuinely unethical, and in some jurisdictions it's becoming **illegal** (the FTC's "click-to-cancel" rule, EU consumer protection directives, California's automatic renewal laws).

**Your backdoor is clever but fragile.** If the PM ever actually tests the flow, you'll catch heat for "not implementing the spec." You're taking on personal risk to partially fix someone else's bad decision.

**What I'd actually recommend doing in parallel:**

- **Put your objection in writing** - email, Slack, something timestamped. "I want to flag that this pattern may violate FTC click-to-cancel rules. Implementing as requested per your direction."
- **Escalate past the PM** if you can - to his manager, to legal, to design leadership. Frame it as legal/business risk, not just ethics.
- **Document everything.** If this company is the kind that builds subscription traps targeting elderly users, you may need that paper trail.
- **Start interviewing.** Seriously. A PM who says "just ship it" to this kind of concern is telling you about the company's values.

You shouldn't have to smuggle basic decency into your codebase through CSS tricks.
